[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] Since September 2024, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] The **`content-visibility`** CSS property controls whether or not an element renders its contents at all, along with forcing a strong set of containments, allowing user agents to potentially omit large swathes of layout and rendering work until it becomes needed.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] It enables the user agent to skip an element's rendering work (including layout and painting) until it is needed — which makes the initial page load much faster.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] The element's contents are laid out and rendered as normal.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] The skipped contents must not be accessible to user-agent features, such as find-in-page, tab-order navigation, etc., nor be selectable or focusable.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] This is similar to giving the contents `display: none`.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] The element turns on layout containment, style containment, and paint containment.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] If the element is not relevant to the user, it also skips its contents.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] Unlike hidden, the skipped contents must still be available as normal to user-agent features such as find-in-page, tab order navigation, etc., and must be focusable and selectable as normal.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] Supporting browsers animate/transition `content-visibility` with a variation on the discrete animation type.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] Discrete animation generally means that the property will flip between two values 50% of the way through the animation.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] In the case of `content-visibility`, however, the browser will flip between the two values to show the animated content for the entire animation duration.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] This behavior is useful for creating entry/exit animations where you want to, for example, remove some content from the DOM with `content-visibility: hidden`, but you want a smooth transition (such as a fade-out) rather than it disappearing immediately.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] When animating `content-visibility` with CSS transitions, `transition-behavior: allow-discrete` needs to be set on `content-visibility`.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] This effectively enables `content-visibility` transitions.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] Off-screen content within a `content-visibility: auto` property remains in the document object model and the accessibility tree.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] This allows improving page performance with `content-visibility: auto` without negatively impacting accessibility.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] Since styles for off-screen content are not rendered, elements intentionally hidden with `display: none` or `visibility: hidden` *will still appear in the accessibility tree*.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] If you don't want an element to appear in the accessibility tree, use `aria-hidden="true"`.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] The following example shows the use of `content-visibility: auto` to skip painting and rendering of off-screen sections.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] When a `section` is out of the viewport then the painting of the content is skipped until the section comes close to the viewport, this helps with both load and interactions on the page.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] The `contain-intrinsic-size` property adds a default size of 500px to the height and width of each `section` element.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] After a section is rendered, it will retain its rendered intrinsic size, even when it is scrolled out of the viewport.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] The following example shows how to manage content visibility with JavaScript.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] Using `content-visibility: hidden;` instead of `display: none;` preserves the rendering state of content when hidden and rendering is faster.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] The `content-visibility` property is set on paragraphs that are direct children of elements with the `visible` and `hidden` classes.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] In our example, we can show and hide content in paragraphs depending on the CSS class of parent div elements.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] The `contain-intrinsic-size` property is included to represent the content size.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] This helps to reduce layout shift when content is hidden.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] In this example, we have a `<div>` element, the content of which can be toggled between shown and hidden by clicking or pressing any key.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] In the CSS we initially set `content-visibility: hidden;` on the `<div>` to hide its content.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] We then set up `@keyframes` animations and attach them to classes to show and hide the `<div>`, animating `content-visibility` and `color` so that you get a smooth animation effect as the content is shown/hidden.
[src:lazy-loading/content-visibility] Finally, we use JavaScript to apply the `.show` and `.hide` classes to the `<div>` as appropriate to apply the animations as it is toggled between shown and hidden states.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] The **`decoding`** property of the `HTMLImageElement` interface provides a hint to the browser as to how it should decode the image.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] More specifically, whether it should wait for the image to be decoded before presenting other content updates or not.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] It reflects the `<img>` element's `decoding` content attribute.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] A string whose value is one of `sync`, `async`, or `auto`.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] For their meanings, see the HTML `<img>` reference.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] In the below example, you'll likely get an empty image shown on the page as the image is downloaded.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] A better solution, however, is to use the `HTMLImageElement.decode()` method to solve this problem.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] It provides a way to asynchronously decode an image, delaying inserting it into the DOM until it is fully downloaded and decoded, thereby avoiding the empty image problem mentioned above.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-decoding] This is particularly useful if you're dynamically swapping an existing image for a new one, and also prevents unrelated paints outside of this code from being held up while the image is decoding.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-loading] It’s been available across browsers since March 2022.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-loading] The **`loading`** property of the `HTMLImageElement` interface provides a hint to the browser on how to handle the loading of the image which is currently outside the window's visual viewport.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-loading] This helps to optimize the loading of the document's contents by postponing loading the image until it's expected to be needed, rather than immediately during the initial page load.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-loading] It reflects the `<img>` element's `loading` content attribute.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-loading] A string whose value is one of `eager` or `lazy`.
[src:lazy-loading/htmlimageelement-loading] The `addImageToList()` function shown below adds a photo thumbnail to a list of items, using lazy-loading to avoid loading the image from the network until it's actually needed.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] It’s been available across browsers since March 2019.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] The **`IntersectionObserver`** interface of the Intersection Observer API provides a way to asynchronously observe changes in the intersection of a target element with an ancestor element or with a top-level document's viewport.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] The ancestor element or viewport is referred to as the root.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] When an `IntersectionObserver` is created, it's configured to watch for given ratios of visibility within the root.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] The configuration cannot be changed once the `IntersectionObserver` is created, so a given observer object is only useful for watching for specific changes in degree of visibility; however, you can watch multiple target elements with the same observer.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] Creates a new `IntersectionObserver` object which will execute a specified callback function when it detects that a target element's visibility has crossed one or more thresholds.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] An integer indicating the minimum delay between notifications from this observer.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] The `Element` or `Document` whose bounds are used as the bounding box when testing for intersection.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] If no `root` value was passed to the constructor or its value is `null`, the top-level document's viewport is used.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] An offset rectangle applied to the root's bounding box when calculating intersections, effectively shrinking or growing the root for calculation purposes.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] The value returned by this property may not be the same as the one specified when calling the constructor as it may be changed to match internal requirements.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] Each offset can be expressed in pixels (`px`) or percentages (`%`).
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] An offset rectangle applied to each scroll container on the path from intersection root to target, effectively shrinking or growing the clip rectangles used to calculate intersections.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] The value returned by this property may not be the same as the one specified when calling the constructor.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] A list of thresholds, sorted in increasing numeric order, where each threshold is a ratio of intersection area to bounding box area of an observed target.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] Notifications for a target are generated when any of the thresholds are crossed for that target.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] If no value was passed to the constructor, 0 is used.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] A boolean indicating whether this `IntersectionObserver` is checking that the target does not have compromised visibility.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] Stops the `IntersectionObserver` object from observing any target.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] Tells the `IntersectionObserver` a target element to observe.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] Returns an array of `IntersectionObserverEntry` objects for all observed targets.
[src:lazy-loading/intersectionobserver] Tells the `IntersectionObserver` to stop observing a particular target element.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] Prior to being established as a web standard, web frameworks were generally used to implement lazy loading.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] Since lazy loading decreases bandwidth and subsequently server resources, it is a strong contender to implement in a website, especially in order to improve user retention by having less delay when loading the page, which may also improve search engine optimization (SEO).
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] Since 2020, major web browsers have enabled native handling of lazy loading by default.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] This allows lazy loading to be incorporated into a webpage by adding HTML attributes.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] The `loading` attribute support two values, `lazy` and `eager`.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] Setting the value to `lazy` will fetch the resource only when it is required (such as when an image scrolls into view when a user scrolls down), while setting it to `eager`, the default state, the resource will be immediately loaded.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] There are four common ways of implementing the lazy load design pattern: *lazy initialization*; a *virtual proxy*; a *ghost*, and a *value holder*.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] Each has its own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] With lazy initialization, the object is first set to `null`.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] Whenever the object is requested, the object is checked, and if it is `null`, the object is then immediately created and returned.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] This method is the simplest to implement, although if `null` is a legitimate return value, it may be necessary to use a placeholder object to signal that it has not been initialized.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] If this method is used in a multithreaded application, synchronization must be used to avoid race conditions.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] A virtual proxy is an object with the same interface as the real object.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] The first time one of its methods is called it loads the real object and then delegates.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] A *ghost* is the object that is to be loaded in a partial state.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] It may initially only contain the object's identifier, but it loads its own data the first time one of its properties is accessed.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] For example, consider that a user is about to request content via an online form.
[src:lazy-loading/lazy-loading] At the time of creation, the only information available is that content will be accessed, but the specific action and content is unknown.
